 972    def addCradle(
 973        self,
 974        x: float,
 975        y: float,
 976        hpWidth: int,
 977        height: float,
 978        centered: bool = True,
 979        orientation: str = "horizontal",
 980        supportTop: bool = True,
 981        supportRight: bool = True,
 982        supportBottom: bool = True,
 983        supportLeft: bool = True,
 984    ):
 985        """Adds a pair of recessed hp rails and a hole for modules.
 986        The rail is added to the supports layer, not the panel layer.
 987        You probably want to use `addEurorackCradle()` or
 988        `add1UIJCradle()` instead.
 989        """
 990        # Add the two rails
 991        self.addRail(x, y, hpWidth, centered, orientation)
 992        if orientation == "horizontal":
 993            self.addRail(
 994                x,
 995                y + height - self.config["m3Diameter"] * 2,
 996                hpWidth,
 997                centered,
 998                orientation,
 999            )
1000        else:
1001            self.addRail(
1002                x + height - self.config["m3Diameter"] * 2,
1003                y,
1004                hpWidth,
1005                centered,
1006                orientation,
1007            )
1008        # Cut a hole between those rails
1009        if orientation == "horizontal":
1010            if centered:
1011                self.cutRect(
1012                    x,
1013                    y + height / 2 - self.config["railsHeight"] / 2,
1014                    hp(hpWidth) + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1015                    height + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1016                    0,
1017                    centered,
1018                )
1019                offset = -hp(hpWidth) / 2
1020                x1 = x - 3 + offset
1021                x2 = x + hp(hpWidth) + offset
1022                y1 = y - self.config["railsHeight"] / 2 - 3
1023                y2 = y + height - 2
1024            else:
1025                self.cutRect(
1026                    x - self.config["cradleTolerance"],
1027                    y - self.config["cradleTolerance"],
1028                    hp(hpWidth) + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1029                    height + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1030                    0,
1031                    centered,
1032                )
1033                offset = 0
1034                x1 = x - 3 + offset
1035                x2 = x + hp(hpWidth) + offset
1036                y1 = y - 3
1037                y2 = y + height + 2
1038            w = hp(hpWidth) + 6
1039            h = height + 6
1040        else:  # vertical
1041            if centered:
1042                self.cutRect(
1043                    x + height / 2 - self.config["railsHeight"] / 2,
1044                    y,
1045                    height + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1046                    hp(hpWidth) + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1047                    0,
1048                    centered,
1049                )
1050                x1 = (
1051                    x - self.config["railsHeight"] * 0.7
1052                )  # FIXME: IDK why it needs this number. This prolly breaks alt values.
1053                x2 = x + height - 2
1054                y1 = y - hp(hpWidth) / 2 - 3
1055                y2 = y + hp(hpWidth) / 2
1056            else:
1057                self.cutRect(
1058                    x - self.config["cradleTolerance"],
1059                    y - self.config["cradleTolerance"],
1060                    height + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1061                    hp(hpWidth) + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1062                    0,
1063                    centered,
1064                )
1065                x1 = x - 3
1066                x2 = x + height + 2
1067                y1 = y - 3
1068                y2 = y + hp(hpWidth)
1069            w = height + 6
1070            h = hp(hpWidth) + 6
1071        if supportTop:
1072            self.supportBar(
1073                x1,
1074                y1,
1075                w,
1076                3 + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1077                self.config["railsSupportDepthBack"],
1078                False,
1079            )
1080        if supportBottom:
1081            self.supportBar(
1082                x1,
1083                y2 - self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1084                w,
1085                3 + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1086                self.config["railsSupportDepthBack"],
1087                False,
1088            )
1089        if supportLeft:
1090            self.supportBar(
1091                x1,
1092                y1,
1093                3 + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1094                h,
1095                self.config["railsSupportDepthBack"],
1096                False,
1097            )
1098        if supportRight:
1099            self.supportBar(
1100                x2 - self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1101                y1,
1102                3 + self.config["cradleTolerance"] * 2,
1103                h,
1104                self.config["railsSupportDepthBack"],
1105                False,
1106            )
1107
1108        self.previewPanel(x, y, hpWidth, height, centered, orientation)
1109
1110    def addEurorackCradle(
1111        self,
1112        x: float,
1113        y: float,
1114        hpWidth: int,
1115        centered: bool = True,
1116        orientation: str = "horizontal",
1117        supportTop: bool = True,
1118        supportRight: bool = True,
1119        supportBottom: bool = True,
1120        supportLeft: bool = True,
1121    ):
1122        """Adds a pair of recessed hp rails and a hole for modules.
1123        The rail is added to the supports layer, not the panel layer.
1124        Screw holes are spaced vertically 122.5mm apart for Eurorack.
1125        There are supports around the cradle for increased strength.
1126
1127        This footprint will probbly not work with custom values
1128        without modifying the code.
1129
1130        Printed rails hold modules satisfactorily using M3x8mm screws, and
1131        the holes last a dozen screwing cycles before becoming too enlarged
1132        to hold things well. For increased safety, use longer screws and nuts.
1133
1134        Strongly advised to print with supports, but will still print OK without.
1135
1136        x, y define the center hole of the top rail if centered, that is,
1137        if the rail is 3hp, the coordinates define the center of the 2nd hole.
1138        If not centered, the coordinates define the top-left of the
1139        opening window.
1140
1141        orientation is "horizontal" by default, otherwise "vertical"
1142
1143        supportTop, supportRight, supportBottom, supportLeft can be set to False
1144        to allow stacking rails next to each other."""
1145        self.addCradle(
1146            x,
1147            y,
1148            hpWidth,
1149            self.config["eurorackHeight"],
1150            centered,
1151            orientation,
1152            supportTop,
1153            supportRight,
1154            supportBottom,
1155            supportLeft,
1156        )

1173        There are supports around the cradle for increased strength.

1177
1178        Printed rails hold modules satisfactorily using M3x8mm screws, and

1180        to hold things well. For increased safety, use longer screws and nuts.

1185        if the rail is 3hp, the coordinates define the center of the 2nd hole.

1211    # Every function adding to the supports layer has support at the
1212    # start of the name.

1214    def supportBar(
1215        self,
1216        x: float,
1217        y: float,
1218        width: float,
1219        height: float,
1220        depth: float,
1221        centered: bool = False,
1222    ):
1223        """Adds a box on the supports layer.
1224
1225        x, y define the top-left of the box as seen from the front
1226        """
1227        if not self.config["supportsRender"]:
1228            return
1229        if centered:
1230            x = -self.config["panelWidth"] / 2 + x
1231            y = -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2 + y
1232        else:
1233            x = -self.config["panelWidth"] / 2 + x + width / 2
1234            y = -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2 + y + height / 2
1235        self.supports = (
1236            self.supports.moveTo(
1237                x,
1238                y,
1239            )
1240            .rect(width, height)
1241            .extrude(depth)
1242        )

1248    # Drill template marks are simple cross shapes that will more or less

1253    def markOutline(self):
1254        """Add an outline to the drill template layer. This ensures proper
1255        SVG export. This is automatically done when adding a panel."""
1256
1257        self.drillTemplate = (
1258            self.drillTemplate.moveTo(  # Top
1259                0,
1260                -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2
1261                + self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"] / 2,
1262            )
1263            .rect(
1264                self.config["panelWidth"],
1265                self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"],
1266            )
1267            .extrude(self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"])
1268            .moveTo(  # Bottom
1269                0,
1270                self.config["panelHeight"] / 2
1271                - self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"] / 2,
1272            )
1273            .rect(
1274                self.config["panelWidth"],
1275                self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"],
1276            )
1277            .extrude(self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"])
1278            .moveTo(  # Left
1279                -self.config["panelWidth"] / 2
1280                + self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"] / 2,
1281                0,
1282            )
1283            .rect(
1284                self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"],
1285                self.config["panelHeight"],
1286            )
1287            .extrude(self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"])
1288            .moveTo(  # Right
1289                self.config["panelWidth"] / 2
1290                - self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"] / 2,
1291                0,
1292            )
1293            .rect(
1294                self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"],
1295                self.config["panelHeight"],
1296            )
1297            .extrude(self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"])
1298        )

1300    def markCross(self, x: float, y: float):
1301        """Adds a mark on the drill template layer. At typical synth panel
1302        sizes, it will show up as a cross the perfect size for printing out and
1303        using as a drill template.
1304
1305        x, y define the center of the mark as seen from the front.
1306        """
1307        self.drillTemplate = (
1308            self.drillTemplate.moveTo(
1309                -self.config["panelWidth"] / 2 + x,
1310                -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2 + y,
1311            )
1312            .rect(
1313                self.config["DrillTemplateMarkLength"],
1314                self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"],
1315            )
1316            .extrude(self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"])
1317            .moveTo(
1318                -self.config["panelWidth"] / 2 + x,
1319                -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2 + y,
1320            )
1321            .rect(
1322                self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"],
1323                self.config["DrillTemplateMarkLength"],
1324            )
1325            .extrude(self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"])
1326        )

1328    def markRect(self, x: float, y: float, width: float, height: float):
1329        """Marks a rectangle on the drill template.
1330
1331        x, y define the center."""
1332
1333        self.drillTemplate = (
1334            self.drillTemplate.moveTo(
1335                -self.config["panelWidth"] / 2 + x,
1336                -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2 + y,
1337            )
1338            .rect(width, height)
1339            .extrude(1)
1340            .moveTo(
1341                -self.config["panelWidth"] / 2 + x,
1342                -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2 + y,
1343            )
1344            .rect(
1345                width - self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"] * 2,
1346                height - self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"] * 2,
1347            )
1348            .cutThruAll()
1349        )
1350
1351    def markHole(self, x: float, y: float, diameter: float):
1352        """Marks a circular hole on the drill template.
1353
1354        x, y define the center.
1355
1356        FIXME: Nasty implementation, and requires marking circles before crosses
1357
1358        """
1359        self.drillTemplate = (
1360            self.drillTemplate.moveTo(
1361                -self.config["panelWidth"] / 2 + x,
1362                -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2 + y,
1363            )
1364            .circle(diameter / 2)
1365            .extrude(1)
1366            .moveTo(
1367                -self.config["panelWidth"] / 2 + x,
1368                -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2 + y,
1369            )
1370            .circle(diameter / 2 - self.config["DrillTemplateMarkThickness"])
1371            .cutThruAll()
1372        )
1373        return

1553    ### Potentiometers, rotary encoders, sliders
1554    #######################################################################
1555
1556    def cutPotentiometer(
1557        self,
1558        x: float,
1559        y: float,
1560        notchOrientation: str = "all",
1561        rotaryEncoderNotch: bool = False,
1562    ):
1563        if not self.config["panelRender"]:
1564            return
1565        self.cutHole(x, y, self.config["potentiometerHoleDiameterWithTolerance"])
1566        # List the notches
1567        points = []  # default to "none" configuration
1568        if notchOrientation == "top" or notchOrientation == "all":
1569            points.append((0, -self.config["potentiometerNotchDistanceFromCenter"]))
1570        if notchOrientation == "right" or notchOrientation == "all":
1571            points.append((self.config["potentiometerNotchDistanceFromCenter"], 0))
1572        if notchOrientation == "bottom" or notchOrientation == "all":
1573            points.append((0, self.config["potentiometerNotchDistanceFromCenter"]))
1574        if notchOrientation == "left" or notchOrientation == "all":
1575            points.append((-self.config["potentiometerNotchDistanceFromCenter"], 0))
1576        # Cut the notches
1577        self.panel = (
1578            self.panel.faces(">Z")
1579            .vertices("<XY")
1580            .workplane(centerOption="CenterOfMass")
1581            .center(x, y)
1582            .pushPoints(points)
1583            .hole(
1584                self.config["potentiometerNotchDiameter"],
1585                self.config["potentiometerNotchDepth"],
1586            )
1587        )
1588        # Notch for the encoder
1589        if rotaryEncoderNotch:
1590            self.panel = (
1591                self.panel.faces(">Z")
1592                .vertices("<XY")
1593                .workplane(centerOption="CenterOfMass")
1594                .center(x, y)
1595                .rect(
1596                    self.config["rotaryEncoderWidthWithTolerance"],
1597                    self.config["rotaryEncoderHeightWithTolerance"],
1598                )
1599                .cutBlind(-self.config["rotaryEncoderNotchDepth"])
1600            )

1603        if not self.config["previewRender"]:
1604            return
1605        self.previewCylinderOnFront(x, y, 6, 21)
1606        self.previewCylinderOnFront(x, y, 9.6, 1.6)
1607        self.previewCylinderOnBack(x, y, 16, 8)
1608        if lugsOrientation == "all" or lugsOrientation == "bottom":
1609            self.previewBoxOnBack(x, y + 8, 15, 18, 2.4)
1610        if lugsOrientation == "top":
1611            self.previewBoxOnBack(x, y - 8, 15, 18, 2.4)
1612        if lugsOrientation == "left":
1613            self.previewBoxOnBack(x - 8, y, 18, 15, 2.4)
1614        if lugsOrientation == "right":
1615            self.previewBoxOnBack(x + 8, y, 18, 15, 2.4)

Each SynthPrinter object corresponds to a panel. You must add one, and only one panel, before performing operations on it.

Once you're done placing elements, you must call render() before exporting your work, to post-process things correctly. Elements will be aligned and oriented wrong if you skip this call.

The naming convention of methods is as follows:

  • addX(): calls methods such as cutX(), previewX(), etc, operating on multiple layers. Skips drawing to disabled layers for performance, so disable unnecessary layers in the constructor while making your layout. In most cases, you want to call those methods instead of making the individual calls bundled in the addX() methods.
  • cutX(): makes a hole for X on the panel layer
  • markX(): draws marks for X on the drillTemplate layer. Exporting a drill template is a WIP, it still takes a bit of tinkering to make the PDF the proper size.
  • previewX(): draws boxes and cylinders to preview the size of footprints on the preview layer
  • embossX(): creates an element on the emboss layer. You can only 3D print quality embossings if you orient your panel with the back as the first layer. Not implemented yet
  • engraveX(): carves an engraving that does not cut all the way through the panel layer
  • supportX(): creates an element on the supports layer, used to strenghten panels and hold in place PCBs. You can only 3D print supports if you orient your panel with the front as the first layer.

Be sure to take a look at the bundled examples!

You can override any of the defaultConfig settings by passing them as a parameter to the constructor. Look at the code for the full list of settings. Some are dynamically calculated from other settings, in particular, the tolerances of most elements are expressed as a multiplier of the main tolerance value.

For example, to replace the main tolerance value of 0.4mm, create a new object as follows:

sp = SynthPrinter(
    tolerance=0.6,
)

defaultConfig values are mostly dimensions that have been tested to work well with 3D printing. You are encouraged to try out the defaults first. But with a different process than FDM 3D printing, you will want to make your own configuration profile.

def addPanel(self, width: float, height: float, screwSlots: str = 'auto'): 
499    def addPanel(
500        self,
501        width: float,
502        height: float,
503        screwSlots: str = "auto",
504    ):
505        """Adds a rectangular panel of arbitrary dimensions.
506        You can only add one.
507
508        Screw slots in the corners provide better tolerances than holes
509        in a DIY printed system. If the panel is too small for four slots,
510        there will be only two by default.
511
512
513        TODO: Add Slots to the drill template
514
515
516        screwSlots: options are "auto", "auto-tlbr", "auto-trbl", "auto-center", "none", "all", "tlbr", "trbl", "center"
517        """
518
519        if self.panelAdded == True:
520            raise Warning("Only one panel can be added")
521        else:
522            self.panelAdded = True
523
524        self.config["panelWidth"] = width
525        self.config["panelHeight"] = height
526
527        # Make the main panel shape
528        self.panel = self.panel.box(
529            self.config["panelWidth"],
530            self.config["panelHeight"],
531            self.config["panelThickness"],
532        )
533
534        # Initialize the drill template
535        self.markOutline()
536
537        # Do we add screw slots?
538        # default to "none" configuration
539        screwSlotTopLeft = False
540        screwSlotTopCenter = False
541        screwSlotTopRight = False
542        screwSlotBottomLeft = False
543        screwSlotBottomCenter = False
544        screwSlotBottomRight = False
545        if (  # If too small for 4 slots
546            self.config["m3screwSlotWidth"] * 2
547            + (
548                self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromSide"]
549                - self.config["m3screwSlotWidth"] / 2
550            )
551            * 2
552        ) > self.config["panelWidth"]:
553            if screwSlots == "auto":
554                screwSlots = "tlbr"
555            if screwSlots == "auto-tlbr":
556                screwSlots = "tlbr"
557            if screwSlots == "auto-trbl":
558                screwSlots = "trbl"
559            if screwSlots == "auto-center":
560                screwSlots = "center"
561        else:  # Large enough for 4 slots
562            if screwSlots == "auto":
563                screwSlots = "all"
564            if screwSlots == "auto-tlbr":
565                screwSlots = "all"
566            if screwSlots == "auto-trbl":
567                screwSlots = "all"
568            if screwSlots == "auto-center":
569                screwSlots = "all"
570        if screwSlots == "tlbr":
571            screwSlotTopLeft = True
572            screwSlotBottomRight = True
573        if screwSlots == "trbl":
574            screwSlotTopRight = True
575            screwSlotBottomLeft = True
576        if screwSlots == "center":
577            screwSlotTopCenter = True
578            screwSlotBottomCenter = True
579        if screwSlots == "all":
580            screwSlotTopLeft = True
581            screwSlotTopRight = True
582            screwSlotBottomLeft = True
583            screwSlotBottomRight = True
584
585        screwPoints = []
586        if screwSlotTopLeft:
587            screwPoints.append(
588                (
589                    self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromSide"],
590                    self.config["panelHeight"]
591                    - self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromTop"],
592                )
593            )
594        if screwSlotTopCenter:
595            screwPoints.append(
596                (
597                    self.config["panelWidth"] / 2,
598                    self.config["panelHeight"]
599                    - self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromTop"],
600                )
601            )
602        if screwSlotTopRight:
603            screwPoints.append(
604                (
605                    self.config["panelWidth"]
606                    - self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromSide"],
607                    self.config["panelHeight"]
608                    - self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromTop"],
609                )
610            )
611        if screwSlotBottomLeft:
612            screwPoints.append(
613                (
614                    self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromSide"],
615                    self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromBottom"],
616                )
617            )
618        if screwSlotBottomCenter:
619            screwPoints.append(
620                (
621                    self.config["panelWidth"] / 2,
622                    self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromBottom"],
623                )
624            )
625        if screwSlotBottomRight:
626            screwPoints.append(
627                (
628                    self.config["panelWidth"]
629                    - self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromSide"],
630                    self.config["m3screwSlotDistanceFromBottom"],
631                )
632            )
633        if screwPoints != []:
634            self.panel = (
635                self.panel.faces(">Z")
636                .workplane()
637                .center(-self.config["panelWidth"] / 2, -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2)
638                .pushPoints(screwPoints)
639                .slot2D(
640                    self.config["m3screwSlotWidth"],
641                    self.config["m3screwSlotHeight"],
642                    0,
643                )
644                .cutThruAll()
645            )

Adds a rectangular panel of arbitrary dimensions. You can only add one.

Screw slots in the corners provide better tolerances than holes in a DIY printed system. If the panel is too small for four slots, there will be only two by default.

def cutPanelWidthTolerance(self): 
708    def cutPanelWidthTolerance(self):
709        """Automatically called during `render()` for Eurorack and 1UIJ:
710        makes the panel a bit smaller than its nominal size laterally to account
711        for thermal expansion and misaligned neighboring panels.
712        Kosmo panels are naturally a bit smaller than the hp grid (they are on a
713        25mm grid, while hp are on a 5.08mm grid), as a result, they don't need
714        this shave.
715        """
716        # FIXME: Trial and error values that make no sense.
717        # Something's broken elsewhere!
718        # FIXME: Test print Euro / IJ: Do the tolerances provide enough extrusions?
719        if self.config["panelWidthTolerance"] == 0:
720            return
721        self.cutRect(
722            0,
723            0,
724            self.config["panelWidthTolerance"],
725            self.config["panelHeight"] * 2,
726            False,
727        )
728
729        self.cutRect(
730            self.config["panelWidth"] - self.config["panelWidthTolerance"] / 2,
731            0,
732            self.config["panelWidthTolerance"],
733            self.config["panelHeight"] * 2,
734            False,
735        )

Automatically called during render() for Eurorack and 1UIJ: makes the panel a bit smaller than its nominal size laterally to account for thermal expansion and misaligned neighboring panels. Kosmo panels are naturally a bit smaller than the hp grid (they are on a 25mm grid, while hp are on a 5.08mm grid), as a result, they don't need this shave.

def cutPotentiometer( self, x: float, y: float, notchOrientation: str = 'all', rotaryEncoderNotch: bool = False): 
1556    def cutPotentiometer(
1557        self,
1558        x: float,
1559        y: float,
1560        notchOrientation: str = "all",
1561        rotaryEncoderNotch: bool = False,
1562    ):
1563        if not self.config["panelRender"]:
1564            return
1565        self.cutHole(x, y, self.config["potentiometerHoleDiameterWithTolerance"])
1566        # List the notches
1567        points = []  # default to "none" configuration
1568        if notchOrientation == "top" or notchOrientation == "all":
1569            points.append((0, -self.config["potentiometerNotchDistanceFromCenter"]))
1570        if notchOrientation == "right" or notchOrientation == "all":
1571            points.append((self.config["potentiometerNotchDistanceFromCenter"], 0))
1572        if notchOrientation == "bottom" or notchOrientation == "all":
1573            points.append((0, self.config["potentiometerNotchDistanceFromCenter"]))
1574        if notchOrientation == "left" or notchOrientation == "all":
1575            points.append((-self.config["potentiometerNotchDistanceFromCenter"], 0))
1576        # Cut the notches
1577        self.panel = (
1578            self.panel.faces(">Z")
1579            .vertices("<XY")
1580            .workplane(centerOption="CenterOfMass")
1581            .center(x, y)
1582            .pushPoints(points)
1583            .hole(
1584                self.config["potentiometerNotchDiameter"],
1585                self.config["potentiometerNotchDepth"],
1586            )
1587        )
1588        # Notch for the encoder
1589        if rotaryEncoderNotch:
1590            self.panel = (
1591                self.panel.faces(">Z")
1592                .vertices("<XY")
1593                .workplane(centerOption="CenterOfMass")
1594                .center(x, y)
1595                .rect(
1596                    self.config["rotaryEncoderWidthWithTolerance"],
1597                    self.config["rotaryEncoderHeightWithTolerance"],
1598                )
1599                .cutBlind(-self.config["rotaryEncoderNotchDepth"])
1600            )

def addPotentiometer( self, x: float, y: float, notchOrientation: str = 'all', lugsOrientation: str = 'all', rotaryEncoderNotch: bool = False): 
1623    def addPotentiometer(
1624        self,
1625        x: float,
1626        y: float,
1627        notchOrientation: str = "all",
1628        lugsOrientation: str = "all",
1629        rotaryEncoderNotch: bool = False,
1630    ):
1631        """Fits most types of panel-mount potentiometers with a 6mm shaft.
1632
1633        There will be four notches around the hole, allowing you to catch the
1634        retaining tab of the potentiometer in the most convenient orientation
1635        possible.
1636
1637        Common rotary encoders such as EC11 could use a thinner panel for the
1638        shaft to protrude sufficiently, in which case, set `rotaryEncoderNotch`
1639        to `True` to cut a rectangle in the back of the  panel.
1640
1641        If you want a knob, add it separately with addKnob()
1642
1643        The orientation parameters are seen from the front, and are:
1644        "all", "none", "top", "left", "right", "bottom".
1645
1646        The retaining notches aren't always on the same side, depending on the
1647        type of potentiometer! If in doubt, just leave it to "all" to add 4 notches.
1648
1649        The preview size for the lugs doesn't account for the possibility of bending them,
1650        so it might be safe to have this area overlap other stuff a little.
1651        """
1652        self.cutPotentiometer(x, y, notchOrientation, rotaryEncoderNotch)
1653        self.previewPotentiometer(x, y, lugsOrientation)
1654        self.markPotentiometer(x, y)

Fits most types of panel-mount potentiometers with a 6mm shaft.

There will be four notches around the hole, allowing you to catch the retaining tab of the potentiometer in the most convenient orientation possible.

Common rotary encoders such as EC11 could use a thinner panel for the shaft to protrude sufficiently, in which case, set rotaryEncoderNotch to True to cut a rectangle in the back of the panel.

If you want a knob, add it separately with addKnob()

The orientation parameters are seen from the front, and are: "all", "none", "top", "left", "right", "bottom".

The retaining notches aren't always on the same side, depending on the type of potentiometer! If in doubt, just leave it to "all" to add 4 notches.

The preview size for the lugs doesn't account for the possibility of bending them, so it might be safe to have this area overlap other stuff a little.

def cutDisplayWindow( self, x: float, y: float, windowWidth: float = 30, windowHeight: float = 15, windowHorizontalOffset: float = 0, windowVerticalOffset: float = -5, screwsHorizontalDistance: float = 40, screwsVerticalDistance: float = 40, addScrews: bool = True): 
2014    def cutDisplayWindow(
2015        self,
2016        x: float,
2017        y: float,
2018        windowWidth: float = 30,
2019        windowHeight: float = 15,
2020        windowHorizontalOffset: float = 0,
2021        windowVerticalOffset: float = -5,
2022        screwsHorizontalDistance: float = 40,
2023        screwsVerticalDistance: float = 40,
2024        addScrews: bool = True,
2025    ):
2026        # FIXME: This is the nastiest way possible to implement a fillet
2027        # but the only one I could figure out.
2028
2029        cutout = (
2030            cq.Workplane("XY")
2031            .box(
2032                windowWidth + self.config["panelThickness"],
2033                windowHeight + self.config["panelThickness"],
2034                self.config["panelThickness"],
2035            )
2036            .edges(">Z")
2037            .fillet(self.config["panelThickness"] * 0.99)
2038            .translate(
2039                (
2040                    -self.config["panelWidth"] / 2 + x + windowHorizontalOffset,
2041                    -self.config["panelHeight"] / 2 + y + windowVerticalOffset,
2042                    0,
2043                )
2044            )
2045        )
2046        self.panel = (
2047            self.panel.faces(">Z")
2048            .vertices("<XY")
2049            .workplane(centerOption="CenterOfMass")
2050            .cut(cutout)
2051        )
2052
2053        # Next, the actual cutout
2054        self.panel = (
2055            self.panel.faces(">Z")
2056            .vertices("<XY")
2057            .workplane(centerOption="CenterOfMass")
2058            .center(x + windowHorizontalOffset, y + windowVerticalOffset)
2059            .rect(windowWidth, windowHeight)
2060            .cutThruAll()
2061        )
2062
2063        # Now, the screws
2064        if addScrews:
2065            self.panel = (
2066                self.panel.faces(">Z")
2067                .vertices("<XY")
2068                .workplane(centerOption="CenterOfMass")
2069                .center(x, y)
2070                .rect(
2071                    screwsHorizontalDistance,
2072                    screwsVerticalDistance,
2073                    forConstruction=True,
2074                )
2075                .vertices()
2076                .circle(self.config["m2DiameterWithTolerance"] / 2)
2077                .cutThruAll()
2078            )
